abstract: WASHINGTON, March 31. -- "Virginia" Bradley kept up his winning streak at the Benning track to-day and captured two of the six purses offered with Peter Paul and Boney Boy. Incidentally the day marked the first victory of old Boney Boy through the steeplechase field. He was never headed, and won by ten lengths from Agis, the second choice. Chivington, making his first effort of the season, was third. Four other starters fell.

abstract: The officials of the Pacific Express Company have been victimized by a gold brick. For a week the company has been guarding at its main office, 414 North Fourth Street, what it supposed to be a genuine gold brick. It came invoiced as "one gold brick." On this evidence the train messenger saw it safely into the train safe and saw it locked up in the burglar-proof vaults at headquarters.

abstract: BRISTOL, R.I., March 31. -- The remodeled racing schooner yacht Ingomar, which is to compete in English waters, was launched at the Herreshoff yards to-day. abstract: MANCHURIA, the stake of the Russo-Japanese war, is the cradle of the Ta-Tsing or Holy Pure reigning family of China. Of its three provinces -- Mukden, or Shingking Kirin and Tsitsihar -- the Mikado's troops have invaded the first two. The plan seems to be the same as that worked out by Japan in the country three times before -- to half-circle the southern provinces and cut off the enemy's supplies.

abstract: Last week's business was of a cheerful sort. Among the dozen most active and representative properties not one declined. Among all stocks which moved a point or more 45 advanced and 13 declined. Among the bonds there were 25 advances to 6 declines. The reverse of this roseate epitome is that the business was too highly concentrated to indicate any very general improvement among properties, or any wide interest outside of professional circles.

abstract: ALBANY, April 5. -- The Senate to-day passed one of the increase-of-salary bills for New York City opposed by the City Club and other organizations. abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., April 6. -- The Cornell 'Varsity crew and the two junior 'Varsity eights rowed to-night for the first time this year on Cayuga Lake. Coach Courtney followed the men in the launch, and made them pull to Crowbar Point and back, a distance of twelve miles. abstract: LONDON, April 16. -- The settlement this week disclosed an important change for the better in the stock market. abstract: If the weather is as cold to-day as it was yesterday the opening championship game on the Polo Grounds between the New York and Philadelphia teams will be postponed. abstract: The starting point of railroad construction in Russia was about 1843, but the building of the trunk lines dates back to the decade between 1860 and 1870. During this period lines were built connecting each of the more important southern seaports with the agricultural provinces. At this point the Russo-Turkish war of 1878-9 caused an almost entire suspension of railway building.

abstract: The annual report of the Directors of the General Electric Company to the stockholders for the year ended Jan. 31 last shows net profits of $7,865,376, including royalties and profit from securities sold and after allowing for depreciation. abstract: CAMBRIDGE SPRINGS, Penn., April 29. -- The fourth round of the international chess masters' tournament was played to-day, and at the close of play Lasker and Marshall had taken the lead ever Janowski and Mieses. Janowski, however, had left his game against Hodges unfinished, and it will surely be won by the Parisian. Janowski is therefore really the leader, having three straight wins to his credit and an adjourned game in hand.

abstract: Preliminary competitions in foils and sabres were held last night in the gymnasium of the New York Athletic Club for the National fencing championship.
